title: For Sale:   Lee Perfect Powder Measure
postcontent:
New in box - unused
Lee Perfect Powder Measure is best for reloading rifle cases, can also be used for pistol cases.

Best for reloading rifle cases.
Throws charges from 2 to over 100 grains. Eliminates Cut Powder and Jerky Action. A soft elastomer wiper strikes off the metering chamber rather than cut the powder. You'll be surprised at how smoothly the rotor operates. More importantly, you will enjoy the most uniform of charges.

Meaningful Calibration 
A micrometer adjuster that reads directly in cubic centimeters. Just multiply the charge in grains by the cc for one grain and you have the setting. So very much better than a meaningless setting as most supply.

Versatile
The metering chamber is the proper size for large rifle charges and the strike off opening small enough to work well with pistol size charges. The Lee Perfect Powder Measure works fine for charges from two grains to over 100 grains.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Several surplus rifles K98 Arisaka Mosins etc
postcontent:
Collecting is pretty expensive right now, (especially for a min wage student!) so I like to trade around and experience several firearms before moving them on to someone else who'll appreciate them. At the moment I've got five old military guns I'm looking to trade.

Starting from left to right, the first is a non-refurbed M44 Mosin. It's a 44 izshevsk in its original mid-war stock. The bolt and magazine floorplate do not match. It has an excellent bore, not counterbored

Second is a Type 99 Arisaka series 35 Toyo Kogyo arsenal. All numbers appear to match. The bore is dark with some light spotting, but I'm sure it would clean up nice. 

Third is an RC K98 manufactured 1935 by Mauser AG Oberndorf. Bore on this one is excellent and it's a great shooter. Receiver/barrel/stock all match, everything else is mismatched. (trade pending)

Fourth is a Finnish Capture 1938 Tula Mosin Nagant. All #s appear to match, with the bolt being force matched by the finns. Good bore and great shooter. This one almost rivals my 44 PU sniper with match ammo.

Fifth rifle is a Chinese type 24/Chiang Kai-shek rifle. I can only seem to find serials on the barrel, bolt, and floorplate. The floorplate is force matched to the barrel but the bolt does not match. The bore is pretty terrible on this one

May sell but prefer trades
I'm only looking to trade for other old military surplus guns. I apologize for the relatively poor quality pics, if you're interested I'll try to take some better individual pics of each gun

title: For Sale:  AK 47 74-Style Muzzle Brake / Compensator M 14x1.0 LH
location: St. Paul / White Bear / Oakdale, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
7.62x39 "AK-74 styled" muzzle device which features an expansion chamber, two large lateral ports and smaller angled and vertical ports. The impact of the muzzle gasses on the front of the chamber and the sides of the ports pulls the rifle forward and deflects combustion gasses to the sides of the muzzle. At the same time, the vertical ports hold the muzzle down. This design does an excellent job of reducing muzzle climb and felt recoil.
